	abstract = {There is an increasing demand for AI-based teaching and learning as a response to the transformation of the Digital Revolution and more recent changes during emergency online teaching due to crises such as COVID-19. This research explored the incentives encouraging tertiary educators to adopt artificial intelligence (AI)-supported educational technology. This research used a questionnaire method and a 40-item self-development instrument to evaluate "Factors Affecting the Adoption of AI-supported Applications in Higher Education". Tertiary teacher respondents (N = 673) were sufficient to provide a representative snapshot of the educational context in Taiwan. The findings indicated that the estimated value of the direct effect parameter between organizational innovation identification (OII) and AI-supported teaching behavior (AAI-TB) was 0.93. Innovative intentions (II) and AI-supported teaching behavior (AAI-TB) was 0.64, and innovative intentions (II) and organizational innovation identification (OII) was 0.87. These results indicate that teachers' organizational innovation identification had a significant direct effect on their adoption of AI-supported teaching behavior and that teachers II indirectly affected the adoption of AAI-TB through OII. The relationship model that teachers' innovative intentions and organizational innovation identification for adopting AI-supported teaching behavior was validated as a good fit. This research association model can discuss the associations between teachers' interest and intention to use AI-supported educational teaching behavior, given the examined dimensions. The study highlights the vital role educators play in integrating AI technologies into teaching. Therefore, this study provides theoretical and practical implications regarding teaching behavior and can serve as a reference for improving innovative teaching methods. © Beijing Normal University 2024.},
