	pages = {185 - 204},
	doi = {10.1016/B978-0-12-824073-1.00014-9},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85186875093?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {The last several years have seen substantial progress in the development and application of AI in large-scale evacuation modeling. However, many research questions and problems remain to be resolved before AI-based large-scale evacuation models can become a standard modeling practice that is ready to be adopted by practitioners such as emergency managers and transportation engineers. This chapter provides a critical review of AI for large-scale evacuation modeling (with a focus on hurricane evacuation and wildfire evacuation) by highlighting the major breakthroughs in the field. Additionally, a conceptual framework is developed to categorize AI-based large-scale evacuation models into two types, planning models and real-time models. In this work, we explain in detail the data needs, suitable AI algorithms, model training mechanisms, performance metrics, model explainability, and application scenarios of these two types of models. Lastly, we discuss the major challenges and future research directions of AI for large-scale evacuation modeling. © 2024 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.},
